9. Procedures 


Stored Procedures
1. Aim

To create and execute stored procedures for performing INSERT, UPDATE, and DELETE operations on a table.

2. Theory

A stored procedure is a precompiled SQL block stored in the database that can be executed multiple times.

Improves performance
Provides reusability
Enhances security
3. Program / Procedure
Step 1: Create Table
CREATE TABLE Student (
    RollNo INT PRIMARY KEY,
    Name VARCHAR(30),
    Dept VARCHAR(10)
);
4. Create Procedures
a) Procedure to Insert Data
CREATE OR REPLACE PROCEDURE AddStudent(
    p_RollNo INT,
    p_Name VARCHAR(30),
    p_Dept VARCHAR(10)
)
AS
BEGIN
    INSERT INTO Student VALUES (p_RollNo, p_Name, p_Dept);
END;
b) Procedure to Update Data
CREATE OR REPLACE PROCEDURE UpdateDept(
    p_RollNo INT,
    p_Dept VARCHAR(10)
)
AS
BEGIN
    UPDATE Student
    SET Dept = p_Dept
    WHERE RollNo = p_RollNo;
END;
c) Procedure to Delete Data
CREATE OR REPLACE PROCEDURE DeleteStudent(
    p_RollNo INT
)
AS
BEGIN
    DELETE FROM Student
    WHERE RollNo = p_RollNo;
END;
5. Execute Procedures
Insert Records
EXEC AddStudent(101, 'Ravi', 'CSE');
EXEC AddStudent(102, 'Anu', 'ECE');
Display Data
SELECT * FROM Student;
Update Record
EXEC UpdateDept(101, 'EEE');
Delete Record
EXEC DeleteStudent(102);
Verify Final Data
SELECT * FROM Student;
6. Output (What to Write)
Procedures created successfully
Data inserted, updated, and deleted using procedures
Results verified using SELECT
7. Result

Stored procedures are successfully created and executed to perform database operations.
